---

If you Googled something this morning, you probably noticed: Google answered the question before you clicked a single link. That box at the top of the results page — the AI Overview — is Google's attempt to give people what they want without making them visit your website.

And it's working. For Google, anyway.

## What's Actually Happening

Google's AI Overviews now appear on over 60% of searches. They pull information from across the web, summarize it, and present it as a tidy paragraph at the top of the page. For the person searching, it's convenient. For the businesses whose websites provided that information, it's a problem.

Studies from 2025 and early 2026 show that AI Overviews reduce click-through rates by 15-46%, depending on the type of search. That means fewer people are clicking through to your website, even when your content is the source Google is pulling from.

If you run a local business, this matters more than you might think.

## The Local Business Problem

Let's say someone searches "best hair salon in Greenville SC." Before AI Overviews, they'd see a list of websites and Google Business Profiles, click through a few, and decide. Now, Google's AI reads those websites and presents a summary: "Top-rated salons in Greenville include..." with a few names, prices, and highlights.

Here's what can go wrong:

- **Google summarizes outdated information.** Your hours changed last month, but the AI is pulling from a cached version of your site.
- **Google summarizes your competitor's description of your category.** If your competitor has better content about the services you both offer, their framing wins.
- **Google doesn't mention you at all.** If your website is thin on content — a single page with your name, address, and phone number — there's nothing for the AI to pull from.

The businesses that show up in AI Overviews are the ones with detailed, specific, original content on their websites.

## What "Thin Content" Means Now

Five years ago, a basic website with your logo, a few stock photos, and a contact form was good enough. Google would rank you based on proximity and reviews. That still matters, but now there's a new layer: Google's AI is reading your content and deciding whether it's worth summarizing.

If your website says "We offer quality services at competitive prices," that tells the AI nothing. It can't use that in a summary. It can't distinguish you from the 200 other businesses that say the exact same thing.

Compare that to: "We specialize in balayage and color correction for textured hair. Most color appointments take 2-3 hours and start at $150. Walk-ins welcome Tuesday through Thursday."

The second version gives Google something specific to work with. It answers real questions. And it makes the AI Overview more likely to feature your business accurately.

## Your Defense: Three Things That Actually Work

### 1. Structured Data

Structured data is code on your website that tells Google exactly what your business is, what you offer, where you're located, and when you're open. It's not visible to visitors — it's a machine-readable layer that helps Google (and its AI) understand your business without guessing.

This includes your business name, address, phone number, hours, service list, price ranges, and reviews. When Google's AI is assembling a summary, structured data is the most reliable source it can pull from.

Every site we build at Upstate Web Co includes structured data by default. It's not an add-on. It's table stakes.

### 2. Original Content About Your Specific Business

Stock text and template filler are invisible to AI summaries. What works is content that only you could write — details about your specific services, your approach, your pricing, your location, your seasonal offerings.

When we built the site for Chef's Delight, a personal chef business, we didn't use generic food service copy. The site explains their specific cuisine style, how their booking process works, what a typical dinner party looks like, and what's included in the price. That's content Google's AI can actually use, and no competitor can replicate it.

The same approach worked for Peach & Thread Boutique. Instead of "We sell women's clothing," the site describes specific collections, styling philosophy, and what makes shopping there different from a department store. That specificity is what earns visibility.

### 3. Strong Branded Search

Here's something that hasn't changed: when someone searches your business by name, you should own every result on that page. Your website, your Google Business Profile, your social accounts — all consistent, all current, all saying the same thing.

Branded search is your safety net. Even if Google's AI summarizes a generic version of your category, people who already know your name will find you directly. The goal is to make sure they find the right information when they do.

## What This Means for Your Website

This isn't about tricking Google or gaming an algorithm. It's simpler than that: Google's AI rewards businesses that clearly explain what they do on their own website. If you have specific, original, well-structured content, the AI Overview becomes your ally — it summarizes your business accurately and sends interested people your way.

If you have a template site with stock text and placeholder copy, the AI Overview either ignores you or gets it wrong. And you have no control over that.

## Template Sites vs. Custom Sites in the AI Era

This is where the gap between template websites and custom-built sites becomes a real business problem. Template platforms give you the same page structure, the same generic copy prompts, and often the same stock photos as every other business on the platform. Google's AI sees through that.

A custom site built around your specific business — your words, your services, your pricing, your location — gives Google's AI the raw material to represent you accurately. It's the difference between being summarized and being invisible.

## The Practical Takeaway

You don't need to become an SEO expert. You need three things:

1. A website with real content about your specific business (not template filler)
2. Structured data that tells Google the facts (hours, services, location, prices)
3. Consistent information across your website and Google Business Profile

That's it. No tricks. No monthly SEO subscriptions. Just a website that says something worth summarizing.

